data.title: Nate Robinson rises up for Knicks

data.text:
Nate Robinson had another big fourth quarter, scoring 20 points in the final 10 minutes, to lead the New York Knicks past the Atlanta Hawks, 112-104, last night at Madison Square Garden.

The backup guard finished with 24 points, and went on a personal 7-0 run to put New York up 96-85 with just over six minutes left in the game.

Marvin Williams had 28 points and Josh Smith added 26 for Atlanta, while the Knicks’ David Lee had 17 points and 16 rebounds.

76ers 95, Rockets 93 – Andre Iguodala hit a baseline jumper with 36 seconds left and scored 20 points as Philadelphia rallied from 14 points down in the second half to beat host Houston.

Andre Miller added 16 points and seven assists to help the 76ers improve to 9-2 in their last 11. Tracy McGrady scored 24 points for the Rockets.

Raptors 107, Nets 106 – Jose Calderon had 17 points and 11 assists as Toronto beat New Jersey in East Rutherford, N.J. The Nets’ Devin Harris missed a jumper at the buzzer to win it.

Pistons 98, Timberwolves 89 – Rasheed Wallace tied a season high with 25 points and had 10 rebounds to lead Detroit over Minnesota in Minneapolis.

Allen Iverson added 19 points and Antonio McDyess had 14 points and 10 boards off the bench for the Pistons, while Al Jefferson had 24 points and six rebounds for the hosts.

Trail Blazers 88, Bobcats 74 – LaMarcus Aldridge had 25 points and nine rebounds to help host Portland beat Charlotte.

The Bobcats were without leading scorer Gerald Wallace, who suffered a partially collapsed left lung and fractured rib in Tuesday night’s win over the Lakers. He will remain hospitalized for obvservation.

Heat 93, Wizards 71 – Dwyane Wade had 14 points, nine rebounds and nine assists before sitting out the fourth quarter as host Miami rolled Washington to win its third straight. Antawn Jamison had 21 points and 12 rebounds for the NBA-worst Wizards (9-36).

Thunder 114, Grizzlies 102 – Kevin Durant scored 35 points, Jeff Green added 23 as host Oklahoma City recovered after blowing a late 10-point lead to beat Memphis in overtime. Rudy Gay (25 points) forced OT, but the Grizzlies lost their 11th straight.

Hornets 94, Nuggets 81 – Peja Stojakovic matched a season high with 26 points and host New Orleans stifled Denver. Devin Brown added a season-high 18 points for New Orleans, while Kenyon Martin scored 22 points and J.R. Smith had 20 for Denver.

Pacers 107, Bucks 99 – T.J. Ford matched his career high with 34 points, Jarrett Jack added 14 and Indiana held off a Milwaukee comeback bid in Indianapolis.

Mavericks 117, Warriors 93 – Dirk Nowitzki and Josh Howard keyed a game-changing run during the second quarter, and Jason Terry scored 22 points to lead host Dallas past Golden State.

Bulls 95, Clippers 75 – Luol Deng had 23 points and rookie Derrick Rose added 21 points as visiting Chicago blew out Los Angeles in the third quarter.
